#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:5
msgid "Good Integration Practices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:8
msgid "Install package with pip"
msgstr "使用 pip 安裝軟體包"

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:10
msgid ""
"For development, we recommend you use venv_ for virtual environments (or "
"virtualenv_ for Python 2.7) and pip_ for installing your application and any "
"dependencies, as well as the ``pytest`` package itself. This ensures your "
"code and dependencies are isolated from your system Python installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:16
msgid ""
"Next, place a ``setup.py`` file in the root of your package with the "
"following minimum content::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:18
msgid ""
"from setuptools import setup, find_packages\n"
"\n"
"setup(name=\"PACKAGENAME\", packages=find_packages())"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:22
msgid ""
"Where ``PACKAGENAME`` is the name of your package. You can then install your "
"package in \"editable\" mode by running from the same directory::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:24
msgid "pip install -e ."
msgstr "pip install -e ."

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:26
msgid ""
"which lets you change your source code (both tests and application) and "
"rerun tests at will. This is similar to running ``python setup.py develop`` "
"or ``conda develop`` in that it installs your package using a symlink to "
"your development code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:34
msgid "Conventions for Python test discovery"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:36
msgid "``pytest`` implements the following standard test discovery:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:38
msgid ""
"If no arguments are specified then collection starts from :confval:"
"`testpaths` (if configured) or the current directory. Alternatively, command "
"line arguments can be used in any combination of directories, file names or "
"node ids."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:41
msgid "Recurse into directories, unless they match :confval:`norecursedirs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:42
msgid ""
"In those directories, search for ``test_*.py`` or ``*_test.py`` files, "
"imported by their `test package name`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:43
msgid "From those files, collect test items:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:45
msgid "``test`` prefixed test functions or methods outside of class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:46
msgid ""
"``test`` prefixed test functions or methods inside ``Test`` prefixed test "
"classes (without an ``__init__`` method)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:48
msgid ""
"For examples of how to customize your test discovery :doc:`example/"
"pythoncollection`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:50
msgid ""
"Within Python modules, ``pytest`` also discovers tests using the standard :"
"ref:`unittest.TestCase <unittest.TestCase>` subclassing technique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:55
msgid "Choosing a test layout / import rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:57
msgid "``pytest`` supports two common test layouts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:60
msgid "Tests outside application code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:62
msgid ""
"Putting tests into an extra directory outside your actual application code "
"might be useful if you have many functional tests or for other reasons want "
"to keep tests separate from actual application code (often a good idea)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:66
msgid ""
"setup.py\n"
"mypkg/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    app.py\n"
"    view.py\n"
"tests/\n"
"    test_app.py\n"
"    test_view.py\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:76
msgid "This has the following benefits:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:78
msgid ""
"Your tests can run against an installed version after executing ``pip "
"install .``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:79
msgid ""
"Your tests can run against the local copy with an editable install after "
"executing ``pip install --editable .``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:80
msgid ""
"If you don't have a ``setup.py`` file and are relying on the fact that "
"Python by default puts the current directory in ``sys.path`` to import your "
"package, you can execute ``python -m pytest`` to execute the tests against "
"the local copy directly, without using ``pip``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:86
msgid ""
"See :ref:`pythonpath` for more information about the difference between "
"calling ``pytest`` and ``python -m pytest``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:89
msgid ""
"Note that using this scheme your test files must have **unique names**, "
"because ``pytest`` will import them as *top-level* modules since there are "
"no packages to derive a full package name from. In other words, the test "
"files in the example above will be imported as ``test_app`` and "
"``test_view`` top-level modules by adding ``tests/`` to ``sys.path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:95
msgid ""
"If you need to have test modules with the same name, you might add "
"``__init__.py`` files to your ``tests`` folder and subfolders, changing them "
"to packages::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:98
msgid ""
"setup.py\n"
"mypkg/\n"
"    ...\n"
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    foo/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py\n"
"    bar/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:110
msgid ""
"Now pytest will load the modules as ``tests.foo.test_view`` and ``tests.bar."
"test_view``, allowing you to have modules with the same name. But now this "
"introduces a subtle problem: in order to load the test modules from the "
"``tests`` directory, pytest prepends the root of the repository to ``sys."
"path``, which adds the side-effect that now ``mypkg`` is also importable. "
"This is problematic if you are using a tool like `tox`_ to test your package "
"in a virtual environment, because you want to test the *installed* version "
"of your package, not the local code from the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:117
msgid ""
"In this situation, it is **strongly** suggested to use a ``src`` layout "
"where application root package resides in a sub-directory of your root::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:120
msgid ""
"setup.py\n"
"src/\n"
"    mypkg/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        app.py\n"
"        view.py\n"
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    foo/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py\n"
"    bar/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:136
msgid ""
"This layout prevents a lot of common pitfalls and has many benefits, which "
"are better explained in this excellent `blog post by Ionel Cristian Mărieș "
"<https://blog.ionelmc.ro/2014/05/25/python-packaging/#the-structure>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:140
msgid "Tests as part of application code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:142
msgid ""
"Inlining test directories into your application package is useful if you "
"have direct relation between tests and application modules and want to "
"distribute them along with your application::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:146
msgid ""
"setup.py\n"
"mypkg/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    app.py\n"
"    view.py\n"
"    test/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_app.py\n"
"        test_view.py\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:157
msgid ""
"In this scheme, it is easy to run your tests using the ``--pyargs`` option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:159
msgid "pytest --pyargs mypkg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:161
msgid ""
"``pytest`` will discover where ``mypkg`` is installed and collect tests from "
"there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:163
msgid ""
"Note that this layout also works in conjunction with the ``src`` layout "
"mentioned in the previous section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:168
msgid ""
"You can use Python3 namespace packages (PEP420) for your application but "
"pytest will still perform `test package name`_ discovery based on the "
"presence of ``__init__.py`` files.  If you use one of the two recommended "
"file system layouts above but leave away the ``__init__.py`` files from your "
"directories it should just work on Python3.3 and above.  From \"inlined "
"tests\", however, you will need to use absolute imports for getting at your "
"application code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:180
msgid ""
"If ``pytest`` finds an \"a/b/test_module.py\" test file while recursing into "
"the filesystem it determines the import name as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:184
msgid ""
"determine ``basedir``: this is the first \"upward\" (towards the root) "
"directory not containing an ``__init__.py``.  If e.g. both ``a`` and ``b`` "
"contain an ``__init__.py`` file then the parent directory of ``a`` will "
"become the ``basedir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:189
msgid ""
"perform ``sys.path.insert(0, basedir)`` to make the test module importable "
"under the fully qualified import name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:192
msgid ""
"``import a.b.test_module`` where the path is determined by converting path "
"separators ``/`` into \".\" characters.  This means you must follow the "
"convention of having directory and file names map directly to the import "
"names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:197
msgid ""
"The reason for this somewhat evolved importing technique is that in larger "
"projects multiple test modules might import from each other and thus "
"deriving a canonical import name helps to avoid surprises such as a test "
"module getting imported twice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:210
msgid "tox"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:212
msgid ""
"Once you are done with your work and want to make sure that your actual "
"package passes all tests you may want to look into `tox`_, the virtualenv "
"test automation tool and its `pytest support <https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/"
"latest/example/pytest.html>`_. tox helps you to setup virtualenv "
"environments with pre-defined dependencies and then executing a pre-"
"configured test command with options.  It will run tests against the "
"installed package and not against your source code checkout, helping to "
"detect packaging glitches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:224
msgid ""
"Integrating with setuptools / ``python setup.py test`` / ``pytest-runner``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:226
msgid ""
"You can integrate test runs into your setuptools based project with the "
"`pytest-runner <https://pypi.org/project/pytest-runner/>`_ plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:229
msgid "Add this to ``setup.py`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:231
msgid ""
"from setuptools import setup\n"
"\n"
"setup(\n"
"    # ...,\n"
"    setup_requires=[\"pytest-runner\", ...],\n"
"    tests_require=[\"pytest\", ...],\n"
"    # ...,\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:243
msgid "And create an alias into ``setup.cfg`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:246
msgid ""
"[aliases]\n"
"test=pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:251
msgid "If you now type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:253 ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:309
msgid "python setup.py test"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:255
msgid ""
"this will execute your tests using ``pytest-runner``. As this is a "
"standalone version of ``pytest`` no prior installation whatsoever is "
"required for calling the test command. You can also pass additional "
"arguments to pytest such as your test directory or other options using ``--"
"addopts``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:261
msgid ""
"You can also specify other pytest-ini options in your ``setup.cfg`` file by "
"putting them into a ``[tool:pytest]`` section:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:264
msgid ""
"[tool:pytest]\n"
"addopts = --verbose\n"
"python_files = testing/*/*.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:272
msgid "Manual Integration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:274
msgid ""
"If for some reason you don't want/can't use ``pytest-runner``, you can write "
"your own setuptools Test command for invoking pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:277
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"from setuptools.command.test import test as TestCommand\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class PyTest(TestCommand):\n"
"    user_options = [(\"pytest-args=\", \"a\", \"Arguments to pass to "
"pytest\")]\n"
"\n"
"    def initialize_options(self):\n"
"        TestCommand.initialize_options(self)\n"
"        self.pytest_args = \"\"\n"
"\n"
"    def run_tests(self):\n"
"        import shlex\n"
"\n"
"        # import here, cause outside the eggs aren't loaded\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        errno = pytest.main(shlex.split(self.pytest_args))\n"
"        sys.exit(errno)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"setup(\n"
"    # ...,\n"
"    tests_require=[\"pytest\"],\n"
"    cmdclass={\"pytest\": PyTest},\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:307
msgid "Now if you run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:311
msgid ""
"this will download ``pytest`` if needed and then run your tests as you would "
"expect it to. You can pass a single string of arguments using the ``--pytest-"
"args`` or ``-a`` command-line option. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:315
msgid "python setup.py test -a \"--durations=5\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/goodpractices.rst:317
msgid "is equivalent to running ``pytest --durations=5``."
msgstr ""
